Safe Streets For All Through a Regional Lens

Federal Datasets

As part of the Safe Streets for All grant program, applicants were instructed to use:

  1. Motor vehicle related fatality data from between 2016 and 2020 from the Nation Highway Traffic Safety Administrationâs (NHTSA) Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS) dataset.
  2. Population data from the 2015-2019 American Community Survey (ACS).
  3. Underserved community data based on information from the USDOTâs Justice40 Initiative and Historically Disadvantaged Community designation from datahub.transportation.gov/stories/s/tsyd-k6ij.

to represent key information about their service area. Applicants could also use local motor vehicle related fatality data sources.

Fatalities from FARS

Within the Metropolitan Area Planning Council (MAPC) and Boston MPO region, FARS data shows 561 motor vehicle related fatalities between 2016 and 2020.1 Approximately 66% of the fatalities are of people driving or passengers in a motor vehicle. The remaining 34% of the fatalities are cyclists and pedestrians.

Underserved Communities

The definition of âUnderserved Communitiesâ is taken from the USDOTâs Justice40 Initiative. The SS4A NOFO provides a link to a table2 and a tool3 to identify census tracts. An estimated 213,015 people live in 47 census tracts designated as a âHistorically Disadvantaged Community (HDC)â. This represents only 6% of the areaâs population.

As part of the Justice40 Initiative, USDOT quantified the performance of census tracts in six focus areas:

  • Transportation access disadvantage identifies communities and places that spend more, and take longer, to get where they need to go.
  • Health disadvantage identifies communities based on variables associated with adverse health outcomes, disability, as well as environmental exposures.
  • Environmental disadvantage identifies communities with disproportionately high levels of certain air pollutants and high potential presence of lead-based paint in housing units.
  • Economic disadvantage identifies areas and populations with high poverty, low wealth, lack of local jobs, low homeownership, low educational attainment, and high inequality.
  • Resilience disadvantage identifies communities vulnerable to hazards caused by climate change.
  • Equity disadvantage identifies communities with a high percentile of persons (age 5+) who speak English âless than well.â4

Briefly, census tracts are designated as an HDC tract if the tract is in the least advantaged half (or least advantaged quarter for âresilienceâ) of all census tracts for at least four of the focus areas. Many of the census tracts throughout Lynn, Revere, Everett, Chelsea, Malden, Somerville, Cambridge, Boston, and Quincy (among other areas) met the threshold for three of the six focus areas. An additional 600,000 people live in 135 census tracts in the MAPC region meeting three of the six criteria. This represents approximately 24% of the population in the MAPC region.

Regional Datasets

The Boston Region MPO has access to other datasets that describe our understanding of the safety of our streets and the environmental justice areas in the region.

MassDOT maintains a detailed set of data in its crash data portal, known as IMPACT. The portal contains detailed information about crashes, vehicles, and people involved in motor vehicle crashes in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts since at least 2002. The IMPACT portal provides common reports, raw data, and diagnostic tools to identify areas with excess crashes or other high risk areas.

As part of our Title VI obligations, the MPO identifies populations that meet certain criteriaâ¦.

IMPACT: Fatalities and Serious Injuries

Datasets from the IMPACT portal contain information for serious injuries as well as fatalities. The IMPACT dataset goes beyond simply classifying the crash severities. The datasets provide detailed information about where, when, how, and some indications of why the crash happened, who was involved in the crash, what vehicle types were involved in the crash, characteristics of the roadways, and much more. This dataset provides an invaluable source of data to analyze both geospatial trends and temporal trends.

Local Environmental Justice Areas

Throughout this section, the main sources of data are: 2020 US Census Tables P1_001N (Total Population) and P2_005N (Not Hispanic or Latino, White Alone). 2016-2020 5-Year American Community Survey Tables C17002_001 (Total population for whom poverty status Is determined) and C17002_008 (Population earning 2.00 times or more than the poverty level).

In performing its mandated Title VI responsibilities, the Boston Region MPO uses information about peoplesâ race, ethnicity, and income to determine if people can be classified as a minority person or a low-income person.

The Boston Region MPO uses the FTAâs and FHWAâs definition of minority persons: people who are American Indian/Alaska Native; Asian; Black/African American; Hispanic/Latino, regardless of race; and/or Native Hawaiian or other Pacific Islander. A person is considered to have a low income if their annual family income is less than or equal to 200% of the poverty level for their family size.

To classify a census tract as a âminority census tractâ or a âlow-income census tractâ, CTPS calculated whether each census tract exceeded the regional average for each population group. 36.5% of the Boston Region MPO is classified as minority persons and 19.0% of the population is classified as living in a low-income household.5

Approximately 1.6 million people (46%) living in the MAPC region live in a census tract that is classified as minority, low-income, or both.
